<content>
    <para id="id16326807">An understanding of the differences between carbon and silicon is important in understanding the relative chemistry of these Group 14 elements. </para>
    <section id="id16326814">
      <title>Size</title>
      <para id="id16326821">As expected silicon is larger than carbon due to the presence of a second shell: i.e., C = 1<emphasis effect="italics">s</emphasis><sup>2</sup> 2<emphasis effect="italics">s</emphasis><sup>2</sup> 2<emphasis effect="italics">p</emphasis><sup>2</sup> while Si = 1<emphasis effect="italics">s</emphasis><sup>2</sup> 2<emphasis effect="italics">s</emphasis><sup>2</sup> 2<emphasis effect="italics">p</emphasis><sup>6</sup> 3<emphasis effect="italics">s</emphasis><sup>2</sup> 3<emphasis effect="italics">p</emphasis><sup>2</sup>. A comparison of the relative sizes of carbon and silicon are given in <link target-id="id16326908"/>. </para><table id="id16326908" summary="Atomic, covalent, and van der Waals radii of carbon and silicon.">
