    <section id="id16327080">



      <title>Coordination number</title>
      <para id="id16327087">Carbon is known to have a coordination number of 2, 3, and 4 in its compounds depending on the hybridization. A coordination number of 1 can also be considered for CO and CN<sup>-</sup>. Four-coordinate carbon may be considered to be coordinatively saturated. In contrast, in the absence of overwhelming steric bulk, silicon is observed to have coordination numbers of 3, 4, 5, and 6. Examples of five and six-coordinate silicon include Si(acac)<sub>2</sub>Cl and SiF<sub>6</sub><sup>2-</sup>, respectively. Coordination numbers of higher than 4 have been ascribed to the use of low-lying <emphasis effect="italics">d</emphasis> orbitals; however, calculations show these are not significant. Instead, hypervalent silicon is better described by the formation of 3-center molecular orbitals, e.g., <link target-id="id16327244"/>. </para>

      <note id="eip-654">A hypervalent molecule is a molecule that contains one or more typical elements (Group 1, 2, 13-18) formally bearing more than eight electrons in their valence shells. </note>



